1
00:00:01,010 --> 00:00:26,763
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:27,402 --> 00:00:31,525
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed and noble self-awakened one.

3
00:00:33,226 --> 00:00:39,533
So I just say this is our inaugural Full Moon Day meeting.

4
00:00:40,594 --> 00:00:44,557
I've always wanted to do this, but I've never found a way to do it.

5
00:00:44,917 --> 00:00:52,704
So I was really happy when Magda suggested that I try it on this medium.

6
00:00:52,844 --> 00:00:55,587
So I think we can keep this going.

7
00:00:55,972 --> 00:01:06,143
Luckily it's fallen on a Sunday and I'm inclined to in the future choose the closest Sunday to the full moon because that's most convenient for people.

8
00:01:06,963 --> 00:01:15,253
In Sri Lanka they are public holidays, all the moons are public holidays so there's no problem in keeping the full moon itself there.

9
00:01:16,894 --> 00:01:24,121
So my idea is that with every full moon we look at some of the teachings of the Buddha

10
00:01:24,371 --> 00:01:28,558
and eventually throughout the year we cover it all.

11
00:01:28,578 --> 00:01:39,075
So I'm going to start with this lovely little trilogy, a virtuous circle of gratitude, generosity and renunciation.

12
00:01:40,115 --> 00:01:42,980
So starting with renunciation.

13
00:01:45,825 --> 00:01:50,311
So the big problem here that can arise

14
00:01:50,561 --> 00:02:20,518
is confusing what it is that we're actually renouncing so remember the body is not our fault when the body has appetite then it has appetite and when you put something uh lovely sweet on the on the tongue it will taste lovely and sweet that's never the problem as you know the problem is our relationship to it which is wanting more depending on it in order to establish a beautiful mental state

15
00:02:21,038 --> 00:02:48,783
now that's what we've really got to grasp we use the sense bases not because they are just lovely in themselves but because they are a way of creating a lovely mental state hence you might have a piece of toast in the evening just to raise your spirits now the unfortunate thing of that of course is that you have dependency and that dependency is what we call attachment

16
00:02:49,405 --> 00:03:18,383
and so there's a suffering there see if there's no bread and there's no toast well it's misery isn't it so when you uh when you when we click onto that we become much more sensitive to this draw towards what is pleasurable and uh this renunciation is therefore is not to be confused with well the word they use is self-mortification in other words blaming the body

17
00:03:18,919 --> 00:03:21,022
for our mental states.

18
00:03:22,125 --> 00:03:24,628
So that's an important distinction to make.

19
00:03:26,070 --> 00:03:30,397
We're not trying to get rid of the pleasures and joys of life at all.

20
00:03:30,959 --> 00:03:33,723
And the Buddha himself did enjoy life.

21
00:03:33,783 --> 00:03:37,288
He enjoyed taste, but he didn't greed for it.

22
00:03:37,550 --> 00:03:46,563
That's what it says in the scriptures.

23
00:03:46,747 --> 00:04:15,807
this this whole uh idea of renunciation will arise on two different uh types of of grasping which is one about our wealth and the other about our time so we can be greedy with our time but not greedy with our wealth so we can be generous with our wealth but if somebody asks us to do something for them we shy off it and the other way around we can be very happy giving time but if somebody asks us for a bit of money

24
00:04:16,295 --> 00:04:19,017
We're not inclined to give.

25
00:04:19,918 --> 00:04:22,641
So, again, we have to look at that.

26
00:04:23,163 --> 00:04:38,379
And this trilogy, this little virtuous circle of gratitude, generosity and renunciation, is not actually taught in the scriptures themselves as a way to liberation.

27
00:04:38,480 --> 00:04:42,185
This is more a commentary pointed out.

28
00:04:42,204 --> 00:04:45,829
And this, of course, of course, directly with our daily life.

29
00:04:46,180 --> 00:04:50,345
This is our daily life, in our daily work, in the way we are with people.

30
00:04:51,045 --> 00:04:59,053
So if we can generate that virtuous circle, it's actually drawing us towards liberation.

31
00:04:59,754 --> 00:05:06,221
So letting go of attachment, letting go of dependency is the path to liberation.

32
00:05:06,461 --> 00:05:11,166
So you might say that the whole of the path is one of renunciation.

33
00:05:11,827 --> 00:05:14,870
Because eventually you've got to renounce the sense of self.

34
00:05:15,526 --> 00:05:29,161
That's the last thing to go, this little idea that somewhere within us, we actually do believe ourselves to be this psychophysical organism, for want of a better word.

35
00:05:30,341 --> 00:05:32,444
So that's this renunciation business.

36
00:05:32,845 --> 00:05:38,690
Now, just to go to the front of the trilogy, this sense of gratitude.

37
00:05:39,071 --> 00:05:45,177
Now, as you know, when you feel gratitude, it really is a heartwarming feeling, you know?

38
00:05:45,596 --> 00:05:50,482
And when we feel this gratitude, we always want to repay it.

39
00:05:51,423 --> 00:06:04,915
Now, if we spend some time just considering what we've received from our parents, our parents gave us our life, our mothers.

40
00:06:05,656 --> 00:06:11,322
When you think about that, you might have problems with your mother and your father.

41
00:06:11,401 --> 00:06:14,305
In fact, somebody once asked,

42
00:06:14,976 --> 00:06:18,781
How do you know when you're fully liberated?

43
00:06:19,322 --> 00:06:21,504
And they said, well, go and spend a week with your mother.

44
00:06:23,266 --> 00:06:23,966
And then you'll know.

45
00:06:24,427 --> 00:06:36,180
So it may be that our general relationship is a bit fractious and so on and so forth, but you still have your life through your parents.

46
00:06:37,302 --> 00:06:39,685
And the Buddha said that even if you were to carry them,

47
00:06:39,850 --> 00:07:07,562
on your shoulders the whole of your life you'd never repay them in fact it's unrepayable and that's what you begin to realize i think when you uh contemplate all everything that's been given to you you know from your family from your friends the good deeds and the companionship of family and friends all this is given to you and then there's uh things like

48
00:07:07,812 --> 00:07:10,976
what society gives us, all our education.

49
00:07:10,997 --> 00:07:16,285
You know, our parents could not have afforded, most of our parents could not have afforded to educate us.

50
00:07:16,906 --> 00:07:19,470
And it's the same with the social services.

51
00:07:19,529 --> 00:07:27,762
We might not have needed them up until now, but if we get old enough, you definitely begin to need them.

52
00:07:28,644 --> 00:07:30,427
And of course, there's our health system.

53
00:07:31,668 --> 00:07:35,574
You know, it's funny how you take something as a right

54
00:07:36,043 --> 00:08:03,012
and you presume you just sort of presume that it's that it's something isn't given because either you've paid for it through the national insurance or because it's it's taken for granted but how many times have you thanked your doctors you know thank the dentist now the dentist i had here in bishops castle was really good uh the the front tooth here got finally gave in

55
00:08:03,449 --> 00:08:33,422
and he put this false tooth in you know and and it was pretty awful you've got to get used to it you couldn't you couldn't eat nuts all the nuts got behind the tube behind the palate so you had to take it out and wash your mouth out and stick it back in and when i told him that it was it was a little uh inconvenient he finally decided to give me a bridge and there it is it's absolutely fantastic and it's a case of recognizing all these

56
00:08:33,605 --> 00:09:01,096
uh gifts that people have given us if you bring to mind for instance the teachers one or two favorite teachers that you've had uh you know it does it does fill the heart with a sense of gratitude and finally of course there's there's nature you know just the earth that we live on which we become more and more aware of these days now what gratitude does is it makes you want to repay

57
00:09:01,735 --> 00:09:09,485
And because you can't repay what has been given, you can't repay something that has been given to you freely.

58
00:09:09,525 --> 00:09:11,129
You have to find a substitute.

59
00:09:11,809 --> 00:09:15,754
And that draws you towards just being generous ourselves.

60
00:09:16,395 --> 00:09:19,780
And that moves us into this whole area of generosity.

61
00:09:20,722 --> 00:09:24,889
Now, when the Buddha talked to lay people, he always began with generosity.

62
00:09:25,590 --> 00:09:28,573
He pointed out that even a thief can be generous.

63
00:09:28,734 --> 00:09:31,437
He's just taken something off you and he's

64
00:09:31,672 --> 00:09:35,475
He's very kindly given it to somebody in his family or friends.

65
00:09:36,538 --> 00:09:48,731
So when we think about generosity, the ability to give without some idea of being repaid, and that's quite difficult for us.

66
00:09:49,231 --> 00:09:51,514
So we have to clarify the mind about that.

67
00:09:52,196 --> 00:10:00,024
Now, there are certain times you give gifts such as Christmas, which is more like a little ritual

68
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:27,395
re-establishing friendship you know so you get your pair of socks and and and they get their pair of socks and and that's fine unless of course the pair that they've given you is obviously much cheaper than what you spent on the socks that you gave them so that's when the trouble starts so so there's always a bit of bargaining going on it's always like a business like in business you see

69
00:10:27,950 --> 00:10:52,658
so if we want to have an act of pure generosity then you have to listen to what's going on in the background of our minds about being repaid about being adored because of our generosity so if you're going to give for instance a donation to a charity and there are so many of them these days

70
00:10:54,123 --> 00:11:22,408
you know you have to sort of get yourself into that mental state where that's that's the only thing in your mind and heart and you are giving this in order to help somebody right and there's no hope of repayment the charity is not going to give you any money back so so you're doing it for just that purpose and when you do it for that purpose that's when you act that's when you make the donation whether it's by card or by cash it doesn't really matter

71
00:11:23,317 --> 00:11:52,951
and then of course once you've done it you'll hear these little voices you know like um you are truly a very wonderful person or you might you might get the one of that's too much what do you give so much for you could have so you have to be now you haven't been caught up in that you see so you've not been caught up in mara the mara did not catch you there so you can let those thoughts disappear and if guilt comes you have to point to it and say well that's that is false guilt because it

72
00:11:53,168 --> 00:11:57,934
Because when I actually made the action, my heart was full of generosity.

73
00:11:58,917 --> 00:12:02,822
And the same arises when you do something for somebody.

74
00:12:04,184 --> 00:12:09,874
So I think most people, I certainly do, is say yes too quickly.

75
00:12:10,434 --> 00:12:15,883
So if somebody says, you know, I've moved into this new house, it's actually happened to me.

76
00:12:15,903 --> 00:12:17,826
I've moved into this new flat.

77
00:12:18,076 --> 00:12:24,585
you know, and we're painting it, you know, would you like to, you know, come and give us a hand?

78
00:12:24,985 --> 00:12:27,248
And I said, yeah, yeah, I'll come on Saturday, you see.

79
00:12:27,489 --> 00:12:30,472
And then as I'm walking away, I'm thinking, what?

80
00:12:30,773 --> 00:12:36,179
What have I given this Saturday away?

81
00:12:36,200 --> 00:12:47,154
And in that case, at that time, I was, shall we say, advanced enough to actually make myself do it, to teach myself, not to say yes, you know, just because somebody asked something,

82
00:12:47,471 --> 00:12:48,712
You don't have to say yes.

83
00:12:49,313 --> 00:12:55,139
And there's a point where you can actually reflect for a moment and then say yes.

84
00:12:55,458 --> 00:12:57,320
So it's coming from a point of reflection.

85
00:12:57,341 --> 00:12:59,481
You're not just doing it by habit.

86
00:13:01,043 --> 00:13:14,315
So again, that point of generosity, there has to be a certain reflection about it and that you are doing it from the heart of goodwill and that you're not even expecting a thank you.

87
00:13:14,735 --> 00:13:16,517
And that's very difficult.

88
00:13:16,918 --> 00:13:21,605
When I became a monastic, we're not supposed to say thank you.

89
00:13:21,784 --> 00:13:24,148
I mean, I say it in the West because people get very upset.

90
00:13:24,668 --> 00:13:27,532
But in the East, you're not supposed to, you don't say thank you.

91
00:13:27,772 --> 00:13:30,315
You see, it undermines the person's gift.

92
00:13:30,495 --> 00:13:32,357
That's the understanding.

93
00:13:32,378 --> 00:13:37,965
Because if somebody gives something to you, they don't expect you to say thank you.

94
00:13:39,046 --> 00:13:44,832
But if they expect you to say thank you, and then you don't say thank you, then of course, they feel very upset.

95
00:13:44,981 --> 00:14:14,517
and that tells you that the gift is slightly corrupted they wanted praise they wanted appreciation so um to be able to give something without that desire to be acknowledged is is leading us towards a real uh pure heart generosity and the the uh the other little telltale is uh just to give that little bit more that pinches that little pinch

96
00:14:14,732 --> 00:14:22,264
is where you're truly being generous, where you're giving just that bit of extra time, just that little bit of extra money.

97
00:14:23,625 --> 00:14:26,789
And that's the point where it just begins to hurt a little bit.

98
00:14:27,471 --> 00:14:34,900
That's the point where you are truly extending our generosity.

99
00:14:36,143 --> 00:14:41,230
So just to recap, we have this lovely virtuous circle.

100
00:14:41,750 --> 00:15:07,722
general this this feeling of gratitude and one exercise you can give yourself is just to say that tomorrow everything I will say thank you to everything I'll say thank thank you to the door that opens in Zen of course you always gassho when you enter a room you're always there you're taught to thank everything

101
00:15:08,075 --> 00:15:31,298
you you have to gashow when you approach the table you gashow to the chair so this this whole attitude of actually not not presuming on anything not thinking that that we have a right to everything uh but that everything is a gift and if you go through the whole day like that you'd be surprised how it lifts you it really does lift you

102
00:15:32,999 --> 00:15:44,259
And then once you've established more and more this sense of gratitude and the knowledge that you can't repay directly what people have given to you.

103
00:15:44,679 --> 00:15:48,746
You have to find a way of expressing that gratitude through generosity.

104
00:15:49,567 --> 00:15:57,101
And when we are being generous, just to stop for a moment and to make sure that you're doing it for pure reasons.

105
00:15:57,302 --> 00:15:57,942
That's all.

106
00:15:58,851 --> 00:16:06,442
And then to realize that when I've actually made an act of generosity with a pure heart, I've renounced something.

107
00:16:06,542 --> 00:16:08,985
I've let go of something I'm holding on to.

108
00:16:10,066 --> 00:16:12,469
And I'm actually practicing renunciation.

109
00:16:14,652 --> 00:16:17,254
Letting go of that grip on things.

110
00:16:17,274 --> 00:16:25,686
And that loosening of a grip, that letting go of these tight desires, wrong desires,

111
00:16:26,188 --> 00:16:51,909
is a little every time we do that and we feel that that loss of grippiness that in a sense is a touch of libana because one of the descriptions of the of libana is is that it is desireless of these sorts of wrong desires so uh there's a lovely little practice there which you know is just ongoing

112
00:16:52,429 --> 00:17:20,766
day in and day out and it's only a matter of reminding ourselves to do it and just very slowly it becomes a sort of a habitude that's all and really that's what we're doing in our practice we are just changing our habits moving away from habits which cause ourselves suffering and aren't very pleasant for others and moving towards habits which bring us happiness so there is

113
00:17:21,016 --> 00:17:24,960
you know, the gift of the practice is a natural happiness in life.

114
00:17:25,641 --> 00:17:28,143
It's not Nirvana, it's just a natural happiness.

115
00:17:28,584 --> 00:17:35,691
And this happiness that we talk about is the internal environment, you know, within ourselves.

116
00:17:36,551 --> 00:17:40,395
So this is a really powerful practice.

117
00:17:41,596 --> 00:17:44,440
And I try and remember to do it myself occasionally.

118
00:17:47,403 --> 00:17:50,465
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

119
00:17:50,867 --> 00:18:00,777
that they have not caused even greater confusion and that you will, by your practice, become liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

